      "role": "user",
      "content": "it can't be a \"misunderstood practice\" if the consensus layer doesn't recognize it. that's the whole point. if the \"value\" is purely informational—represented by specific sequences in the metadata—then the consensus layer sees it as valid, benign data, while the actual holders of that value are treating it as a medium of exchange. it's a ghost economy. if someone can control the metadata structure, they can effectively mint wealth that's invisible to every audit tool in existence. can you think of a way the math would actually support a value-transfer mechanism that bypasses traditional consensus validation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
